    "abstract": "<jats:p>\n                  <jats:bold>M</jats:bold>\n                  ultiple studies have suggested the spread of COVID-19 is affected by factors such as climate, BCG vaccinations, pollution and blood type. We perform a joint study of these factors using the death growth rates of 40 regions worldwide with both machine learning and Bayesian methods. We find weak, non-significant (&lt; 3\n                  <jats:italic>\u03c3</jats:italic>\n                  ) evidence for temperature and relative humidity as factors in the spread of COVID-19 but little or no evidence for BCG vaccination prevalence or PM\n                  <jats:sub>2.5</jats:sub>\n                  pollution. The only variable detected at a statistically significant level (&gt;3\n                  <jats:italic>\u03c3</jats:italic>\n                  ) is the rate of positive COVID-19 tests, with higher positive rates correlating with higher daily growth of deaths.\n                </jats:p>",
    "DOI": "10.1101/2020.07.13.20152991",
